                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       MCX currency futures
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Mumbai, Aug. 25: The Multi-Commodity Exchange (MCX) has received an in-principal approval from the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) to start trading in currency futures.        
	MCX becomes the second entity after the National Stock Exchange (NSE) to get the market regulators approval. The NSE will begin trading in currency futures from August 29. The Bombay Stock Exchange has also sought Sebis approval for currency futures. However, its application is still pending with the market regulator.        
	Promoter Financial Technologies today informed the bourses that MCX subsidiary MCX Stock Exchange Ltd would begin enrolling members from tomorrow. It has already conducted seven roadshows attended by over 1,000 brokers, bank representatives, exporters, importers and foreign exchange brokers.         
	Currency futures is a foreign exchange derivative contract to buy or sell one currency against the other on a specified future date, at a price decided in the contract.                          
	MCX is setting up a separate unit for offering currency futures.        
	Currency futures is a forex derivative contract to buy or sell one currency against the other on a specified future date, at a price decided in the contract.        
	Early this month. a joint panel of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and the Sebi finalised norms on currency futures. It ruled that only resident Indians could deal in exchange-traded currency futures.        
	Only dollar-rupee contracts will be permitted and the size of each contract should be $1,000. Currency brokers can take client as well as proprietary positions even as it has been stipulated hat the maturity of contracts should not be more than 12 months.        
	In an notice inviting applications for membership to the currency derivatives segment, the NSE stipulated that existing members, members of National Commodity amp; Derivatives Exchange Ltd and new applicants should at least have a net worth of Rs 1 crore. The processing fee for NCDEX members and new applicants is Rs 10,000.                                                                                                                                     
